  "summary": "Jimmy Sycamore and Ronnie DeVille drive to Dean's Priory to meet Gerry Wade's half-sister, Miss Wade. During the journey, Jimmy describes her as a remarkable person. Upon their arrival, they meet the petite, blue-eyed Miss Wade, who is accompanied by two long-eared black dogs. Ronnie informs her of Gerry's death. Although she initially questions if he died from sleeping pills, she eventually asks for more details before stating she wishes to be alone. She informs them that she will arrive at Chimney House later in her two-seater sports car.\n\nUpon returning to Chimney House, Jimmy encounters a tearful Mrs. Cutt. Ronnie, having just left Miss Wade's room, insists that Jimmy enter Gerry's room to pay his respects. Inside, Jimmy observes Gerry's pale, motionless body lying on a bed covered in white flowers. While in the room, Jimmy notices a row of clocks on the mantelpiece and discovers there are only seven clocks present, rather than the eight that were originally part of the prank, leading him to wonder why one is missing.\n\nElsewhere, Lord Kettlemere discusses the nature of successful, self-centered people with his daughter, Miss Elinor Brent, known as \"Bondel.\" Their conversation touches upon land reclaimed from Old Quart. Lord Kettlemere expresses his dislike for oppressive, strong-willed individuals and mentions his opposition to autopsies, noting that a similar issue occurred four years prior involving George Lomax.",
